inch 144Hz 4K gaming monitor sure does a lot. It has an IPS panel with a 2ms (MPRT) response time, 94 percent DCI-P3 coverage, DisplayHDR 400 certification, 2 HDMI 2.1 ports and FreeSync Premium Pro support. It comes in a little bit more expensive than $500, but we&#39;ve often seen it on sale for less.</p><h2> Best monitors under $1,000</h2><h3> ViewSonic ColorPro VP2786-4K </h3><p><core-commerce id="4fd5547c6e344c5d938f05d38bc1d057" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> In this price range you can have resolution, color accuracy or brightness, but not all three. The one with the best balance is ViewSonic&#39;s $1,000 <a data-i13n="cpos:10;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAZ8dZpLOmj2DV7j8u2li0oUmYtR_hIMijq-BQkWmx7uP&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB09Q62HDPX%2F">ColorPro VP2786</a> 27-inch 4K HDR Monitor. The true 10-bit IPS panel covers 98 percent of the DCI-P3 color palette with an excellent Delta &lt;2 accuracy figure, and is certified for soft-proofing by the demanding Fogra print industry. At the same time, it offers HDR10 support, albeit with a limited 350 nits of output. It even includes a “ColorPro” wheel control compatible with Adobe or Capture One apps.</p><h3> Dell G3223Q </h3><p><core-commerce id="3b9f2ee7fa8f48d6a34c1b8d66e91bea" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> The best 4K gaming monitor under $1,000 is <a data-i13n="cpos:11;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAURjkvxOPMzMvXDWXkssfpGPFnN01EVahDuudkmF0QpC&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB09WNG9QWR%2F">Dell&#39;s G3223Q</a> 4K 32-inch HDR 144Hz monitor because of the speed, brightness and compatibility. It has an IPS panel with a 144Hz refresh rate, 1ms GtG response time, 95 percent DCI-P3 coverage and DisplayHDR 600 certification. Plus, it comes with a pair of HDMI 2.1 ports and is both FreeSync and G-Sync compatible.</p><h3> Dell P3223QE </h3><p><core-commerce id="9ce20e9bb9ac4c2d9a09aaa1b6c45e3f" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> Dell&#39;s <a data-i13n="cpos:12;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAXtxBlW8hqifsHq7uIzb1pOYRKRhaQb6z0ZJga865a_W&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB0B76VC145%2F">P3223QE 4K USB-C Hub monitor</a> is productivity-oriented, thanks to the wired Ethernet connectivity and USB-C ports that offer up to 90W of power delivery for laptops. It&#39;s a 4K IPS panel with a 178-degree viewing angle and 350 nits of brightness and support for a billion colors (8-bit + FRC). It offers height, pivot, swivel and tilt adjustment, a VESA mounting interface and DisplayPort/HDMI inputs.</p><h2> Best monitor for Mac users</h2><h3> Apple Studio Display </h3><p><core-commerce id="8a9750cf671b480ea5128c1c27e857ec" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> In general, monitor compatibility issues with MacBooks and Macs are a thing of the past, though you can still experience issues with things like refresh rates, particularly on M1 Macs. If you&#39;d prefer to stay within the Apple family, the most cost-effective option is still the 27-inch <a data-i13n="cpos:13;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAQyw9Egr0LBFNRvII7yFZmHrK8d8vfGUo3d-dnGMzaS6&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FApple-Studio-Display-Standard-Tilt-Adjustable%2Fdp%2FB09V3HP4KL">Apple Studio Display</a> . It supports 5K resolution (5,120 x 2,880) with up to 600 nits of brightness, so it can handle creative chores with ease. It even includes a 12-megapixel UltraWide camera that keeps you in frame via Center Stage, along with a three-mic array.</p><h3> LG Ultrafine 4K and 5K </h3><p><core-commerce id="6861b274748f43f3808ad364a5ea19f4" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> The best third-party option is LG&#39;s $700 <a data-i13n="cpos:14;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9ncC9wcm9kdWN0L0IwOEJDUjg2Mkw_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tZ2ktMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6IjAwN2Y5NmU3LTBlYzktM2E3OS1hNmFlLWQ1MjcxNjQzY2RiZCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAYlxUPR2O62OdgzsLp90MkyoywMbkmwGm0GHiIkxg5zI&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB08BCR862L">UltraFine 4</a> display, also sold on Apple&#39;s Store. With a 24-inch 4K panel, you not only get very high resolution but also 500 nits of brightness (albeit, without HDR capability). It&#39;s color-accurate out of the box, making it great for video- and photo-editing work on a Mac or MacBook. Finally, it supports Thunderbolt 3 with daisy chaining and power delivery, all of which is very useful for Mac users who may want multiple displays.</p><h2> Best Ultrawide monitor</h2><h3> LG 34GP950G-B </h3><p><core-commerce id="ec19b6df4b704faa80c11e885f206bba" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> Ultrawide 21:9 monitors are a great option for some types of content creation, games (particularly driving and flight sims) and productivity work. The best model this year is <a data-i13n="cpos:15;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9MRy0zNEdQOTUwRy1CLVVsdHJhZ2Vhci1SZXNwb25zZS1BZGp1c3RhYmxlL2RwL0IwOTdRRjhDUDM_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tZ2ktMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6IjAwN2Y5NmU3LTBlYzktM2E3OS1hNmFlLWQ1MjcxNjQzY2RiZCJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAZd3bEenl1Ck6QVVrCvCJPj9c2hJTdwT82U-rbBdQcrn&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FLG-34GP950G-B-Ultragear-Response-Adjustable%2Fdp%2FB097QF8CP3">LG&#39;s 34GP950G-B</a> , a 34-inch 3,440 x 1,440 curved monitor. The curved IPS panel supports HDR10 with 400 nits of brightness and maximum (via overclocking) 180Hz refresh rate. It&#39;s also G-Sync and FreeSync compatible (the latter over DisplayPort only).</p><h2> Best portable monitor</h2><h3> LePow C2S </h3><p><core-commerce id="873a8c14e17e4cad89c67b7166b2794c" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> For the best balance of performance and price, <a data-i13n="cpos:16;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAWU08wSGi-UKYAdSFxa5pkqZRvCnhRRU4emU1HWjJAQq&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB09H6RGZCL%2F">LePow&#39;s 15.6-inch C2S</a> is a solid option. It offers decent brightness (220 nits), solid contrast and a very respectable 96.1-percent sRGB gamut coverage. You get a generous selection of ports (one mini-DisplayPort, one mini-HDMI port and two USB-C ports, along with a headphone jack. The metal stand is solid and practical, and it even has built-in speakers of decent quality.</p><h2> Best luxury monitor</h2><h3> ASUS ProArt PA32UCG-K </h3><p><core-commerce id="ec5e673afb5b4bd49fa136f11ed6f4a8" data-type="product-list"></core-commerce></p><p> ASUS still holds the prize for best luxury monitor, but it discontinued the previous mini-LED $4,000 ProArt PA32UCX monitor and replaced it with the $5,000 <a data-i13n="cpos:17;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAV4FPg5xy82EIA4rApTiGNVt1q9qgBtk6yKjf7hwp4kQ&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB08ZC54V7C%2F">PA32UCG-K display</a> . It uses the same mini-LED tech, but ups the ante with 1,600 nits of brightness via 1,152 backlight zones, an HDMI 2.1 port, 4K 120Hz resolution, 10-bit, 98 percent DCI-P3 coverage and an impressive 85 percent Rec.2020 coverage. Oh, and it&#39;s one of the few monitors out there that supports Dolby Vision, along with HDR10 and HLG.</p><p> You&#39;re probably doing it wrong if you&#39;re using a $5K monitor for gaming. However, it does support AMD FreeSync (good for gaming creation) and has a 5-millisecond response time, very respectable for a display essentially designed for professional colorists. And to that end, color accuracy is calibrated to Delta E &lt; 1 and it&#39;s a true 10-bit panel delivering billions of colors. To verify that, it even comes with an X-rite i1 Display Pro color calibrator, normally sold separately for around $500.</p><p> On top of this model, ASUS now makes several slightly less bright and less expensive variants, namely the $4,180 <a data-i13n="elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:;cpos:18;pos:1" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAQmWPCyLh1cJJUlw-YLdKwyg1UntkbH0_Mqqpea3RUH6&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2Fgp%2Fproduct%2FB088MKPYD4%2Fref%3Das_li_ss_tl" data-demonetize-referrer="https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B088MKPYD4/ref=as_li_ss_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;linkCode=ll1&amp;tag=buyersguide2022-20&amp;language=en_US" class="rapid-with-clickid">PA32UCX-PK</a> , (plus -P, and -K variants with slightly different features), offering 1,200 nits of brightness and a 60Hz (not 120Hz) refresh rate. Specs are nearly identical otherwise.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/how-to-buy-a-monitor-143000069.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/how-to-buy-a-monitor-143000069.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 007f96e7-0ec9-3a79-a6ae-d5271643cdbd</guid><dc:creator>史蒂夫·登特</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher>恩杰特</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder>恩杰特</dc:rightsholder><pubDate>Mon, 17 Jul 2023 18:15:20 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1689617720</ingested><modified> 2023-07-17T18:15:48+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[news]]></category><category><![CDATA[refreshrate]]></category><category><![CDATA[entertainment]]></category><category><![CDATA[HDR]]></category><category><![CDATA[4K]]></category><category><![CDATA[display]]></category><category><![CDATA[thebuyersguide]]></category><category><![CDATA[commerce]]></category><category><![CDATA[resolution]]></category><category><![CDATA[contentcreation]]></category><category><![CDATA[gear]]></category><category><![CDATA[monitors]]></category><category><![CDATA[ElectronicEquipment,Instruments&Components]]></category><category><![CDATA[Entertainment(general)]]></category><category><![CDATA[Arts&Entertainment]]></category><category><![CDATA[ElectronicsAccessories]]></category><category><![CDATA[OfficeElectronics]]></category><category><![